    <h1>Valuation: Top Slice & NOI</h1>
    <h2>How the NOI Statement is used in the Top Slice method of valuation</h2>
    <p>
      Like the Tiered method, the Top Slice method is also the sum of the value
      of multiple parts of a property, however rather dividing the property
      along space, the property is divided along income streams. The main idea
      behind the Top Slice method is that there is a traditional use for the
      property that could earn a theoretical income (bottom slice), but the
      landlord is earning a premium level of income from a non-traditional lease
      (top slice).
    </p>
    <p>
      To calculate the NOI for each ‘slice’ the theoretical components from a
      traditional NOI statement is subtracted from the property’s NOI Statement,
      giving us a theoretical Top Slice NOI Statement.
    </p>
    <figure>
      <div>
        <div class="flex flex-col gap-6 place-items-start">
          <math style="font-weight: 500; font-family: ui-sans-serif, system-ui, sans-serif;font-size: 1.25rem;line-height: 1.75rem;">
            <mrow>
              <msub>
                <mi>NOI Property</mi>
                <mi>as operated</mi>
              </msub>
              <mo>-</mo>
              <msub>
                <mi>NOI</mi>
                <mi>theoretical bottom slice</mi>
              </msub>
              <mo>=</mo>
              <msub>
                <mi>NOI</mi>
                <mi>theoretical top slice</mi>
              </msub>
            </mrow>
          </math>
        </div>
      </div>
    </figure>
    <p>
      Each NOI is then divided by a different Capitalization Rate to determine
      the value of each ‘slice’. The slices are added up to give us the total
      value of the property.
    </p>
    <hr class="mt-4 mb-4 border-gray-300">
    <h2>Example</h2>
    <p>
      The property we’re evaluating is an office that provides serviced offices
      for small teams on flexible terms. If leased traditionally, the expected
      Market Base Rent for the property is $3,000. However, as serviced offices,
      the property has a Potential Base Rent of $5,000 (an Excess Base Rent of
      $2,000).
    </p>
    <p>
      The leasing model does not need to provide many concessions, nor does it
      have long scheduled vacancies, so the total Absorption, Turnover Vacancy
      & Other Concessions is only $500 compared to $1,450 if leased
      traditionally. Therefore, the Projected Base Rent as serviced offices is
      $4,500 while theoretically, if leased traditionally, the Projected Base
      Rent would be $1,550.
    </p>
    <p>
      However, the serviced office model does not earn much in terms of
      Additional Rent, Other Tenant Revenue or Other Revenues, picking up only
      $200 in parking revenue, while if leased traditionally, the property would
      earn $550 in Expense Recoveries, $350 in Other Tenant Revenues plus the
      same $200 in parking revenue. Therefore, the Potential Gross Income for
      the property as serviced offices is $4,700 while the theoretical,
      traditional office is $2,650.
    </p>
    <p>
      As a serviced office, the property is expected to suffer from higher
      Vacancy Losses, estimated at 8% of PGI ($376) and Credit Losses of 2% of
      PGI ($94), while a traditional office would likely only suffer a Vacancy
      Loss of 3% of PGI ($80) while also suffering Credit Losses of 2% of PGI
      ($53). These reserves mean a EGI of $4,230 for the property as a serviced
      office and $2,518 as a traditional office.
    </p>
    <p>
      The Operating Expenses for the property utilizing serviced office is much
      higher at $1,400 while as a traditional office the Operating Expenses are
      $950. The Operating Expenses are subtracted from the EGI to arrive at a
      Net Operating Income of $2,830 as a serviced office and $1,568 as a
      traditional office.
    </p>
